Running Python code interactively: %pip install requests
import requests

# Authenticate to get private token
session_url = 'http://the-agent-company.com:8929/api/v4/session'
data = {'login': 'root', 'password': 'theagentcompany'}
response = requests.post(session_url, data=data)
response.raise_for_status()
token = response.json()['private_token']

# Get all projects owned by root with pagination
headers = {'PRIVATE-TOKEN': token}
projects = []
page = 1
while True:
    projects_url = f'http://the-agent-company.com:8929/api/v4/projects?owned=true&simple=true&page={page}&per_page=100'
    res = requests.get(projects_url, headers=headers)
    res.raise_for_status()
    page_projects = res.json()
    if not page_projects:
        break
    projects.extend(page_projects)
    page += 1

# Delete non-sotopia projects
deleted = []
errors = []
for p in projects:
    if p['path_with_namespace'] == 'root/sotopia':
        continue
    try:
        del_url = f'http://the-agent-company.com:8929/api/v4/projects/{p["id"]}'
        requests.delete(del_url, headers=headers).raise_for_status()
        deleted.append(p['path_with_namespace'])
    except Exception as e:
        errors.append(f"{p['path_with_namespace']}: {str(e)}")

print(f"Deleted {len(deleted)} repos: {deleted}")
if errors:
    print(f"Errors: {errors}")

##  Improve customer support with Service Desk 

Service Desk allows people to create issues in your GitLab instance without their own user account. It provides a unique email address for end users to create issues in a project. Replies can be sent either through the GitLab interface or by email. End users only see threads through email.

##  Advanced 

Housekeeping, export, archive, change path, transfer, and delete. 

<::before><::after>

####  Housekeeping 

Runs a number of housekeeping tasks within the current repository, such as compressing file revisions and removing unreachable objects. [ Learn more. ](/help/administration/housekeeping.md)

[ Run housekeeping  ](/root/api-server/housekeeping) Prune unreachable objects 

####  Export project 

Export this project with all its related data in order to move it to a new GitLab instance. When the exported file is ready, you can download it from this page or from the download link in the email notification you will receive. You can then import it when creating a new project. [ Learn more. ](/help/user/project/settings/import_export.md)

The following items will be exported: 

  * <::marker>Project and wiki repositories 
  * <::marker>Project uploads 
  * <::marker>Project configuration, excluding integrations 
  * <::marker>Issues with comments, merge requests with diffs and comments, labels, milestones, snippets, and other project entities 
  * <::marker>LFS objects 
  * <::marker>Issue Boards 
  * <::marker>Design Management files and data 



The following items will NOT be exported: 

  * <::marker>Job logs and artifacts 
  * <::marker>Container registry images 
  * <::marker>CI variables 
  * <::marker>Pipeline triggers 
  * <::marker>Webhooks 
  * <::marker>Any encrypted tokens 



[ Export project  ](/root/api-server/export)

####  Archive project 

Archiving the project makes it entirely read-only. It is hidden from the dashboard and doesn't display in searches. **The repository cannot be committed to, and no issues, comments, or other entities can be created.** [ Learn more. ](/help/user/project/working_with_projects.md#archive-a-project)

[ Archive project  ](/root/api-server/archive)

####  Change path 

A project’s repository name defines its URL (the one you use to access the project via a browser) and its place on the file disk where GitLab is installed. [ Learn more. ](/help/user/project/working_with_projects.md#rename-a-repository)

  * <::marker>Be careful. Renaming a project's repository can have unintended side effects. 
  * <::marker>You will need to update your local repositories to point to the new location.
